When larvae are analyzed using our ICA approach, only a small number of ICs tend to dominate LFP traces from untreated scn1lab mutants (“low-complexity” LFPs), while traces from sibling controls comprise a far greater variety of ICs (“complex” LFPs; Fig. 3a). To quantify the efficacy of compounds in modulating LFP complexity, we developed an IC complexity score based on ICA at 4-h post exposure. To calculate this metric, we first rank order ICs for each compound based on intensity and then normalize all subsequent ICs to the first IC (ICi/IC1). Ineffective compounds and untreated mutants have low-complexity LFP signals (dominated by a few strong ICs), so normalized values drop off rapidly in the lower-ranked ICs. In contrast, complex LFPs from sibling controls and from mutants with “corrected” LFP patterns show less rapid attenuation of lower-ranked ICs (Supplementary Fig. 8a). The ability of a compound to restore LFP complexity in scn1lab mutants is quantified by first calculating two metrics: (1) \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
